    "## 4. Modern approaches to causal inference\n",
    "\n",
    "This workbook introduces three major conceptual tools used today:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. **Mendelian randomisation (MR)** – instrumental variable reasoning using genetic variants.\n",
    "2. **Negative controls** – detecting uncontrolled confounding or measurement bias.\n",
    "3. **Counterfactuals and the potential outcomes framework** – the formal language of causality.\n",
    "\n",
    "These methods help us articulate assumptions and evaluate whether a study's design and data can support causal claims.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "mr_text_only",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 5. Mendelian randomisation (MR) – conceptual overview\n",
    "\n",
    "Mendelian randomisation interprets genetic variants as **instrumental variables**. The key idea is that alleles are randomly allocated at conception, creating a natural experiment.\n",
    "\n",
    "MR rests on three assumptions:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. **Relevance:** the genetic variant is associated with the exposure (for example, BMI).\n",
    "2. **Independence:** the variant is not associated with confounders of the exposure–outcome relationship.\n",
    "3. **Exclusion restriction:** the variant affects the outcome only through the exposure (no pleiotropy).\n",
    "\n",
    "In nutritional epidemiology, MR has been applied to questions such as:\n",
    "\n",
    "- Whether vitamin D affects cardiovascular disease.\n",
    "- Whether lifelong differences in alcohol consumption influence blood pressure.\n",
    "- Whether BMI causally contributes to diabetes and hypertension.\n",
    "\n",
    "We do **not** perform an MR analysis in this workbook. Instead, we highlight that MR can complement observational research when valid instruments exist. However, MR is not a universal solution—pleiotropy, weak instruments, and population structure limit applicability.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "negative_controls",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 6. Negative controls\n",
    "\n",
    "A **negative control** is a variable that should show **no association** with the outcome (or exposure) if the assumed causal model is correct. Finding a non-zero association signals problems such as:\n",
    "\n",
    "- residual confounding,\n",
    "- measurement error,\n",
    "- selection bias.\n",
    "\n",
    "Negative controls come in two types:\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Negative control exposure:** an exposure that should not plausibly affect the outcome.\n",
    "- **Negative control outcome:** an outcome that should not plausibly be affected by the exposure.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 6.1 Example using the FB2NEP cohort\n",
    "\n",
    "We construct a synthetic variable that has no relationship to blood pressure. Any apparent association indicates sampling error or uncontrolled confounding.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
