   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 7. Counterfactuals and the potential outcomes framework\n",
    "\n",
    "Modern causal inference is built on **counterfactual reasoning**. Every causal question implicitly compares two potential states of the same individual:\n",
    "\n",
    "- \( Y(1) \): the outcome if the person were exposed,\n",
    "- \( Y(0) \): the outcome if the person were unexposed.\n",
    "\n",
    "The **individual causal effect** is:\n",
    "\n",
    "\\[\n",
    "Y(1) - Y(0).\n",
    "\\]\n",
    "\n",
    "Of course, we cannot observe both for the same person. This is the **fundamental problem of causal inference**. Identification requires assumptions and study designs that allow us to approximate the missing counterfactual.\n",
    "\n",
    "Counterfactual reasoning underpins all modern methods, including MR, negative controls, natural experiments, quasi-experiments, and trial emulation. Even simple regression attempts to estimate differences in expected potential outcomes, though it relies heavily on assumptions such as no unmeasured confounding.\n"
   ]
  },
